{
  "text": "General methods for the nanofabrication of quartz include chemical etching, plasma etching and reactive ion etching [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . However, the use of these techniques tends to be limited by such disadvantages as environmental pollution, poor resolution and low efficiency [CITATION_4] . Focused ion beam (FIB) technology is advantageous for material processing at nanoscale because of its high machining precision [CITATION_5] , but the ion beam may cause undesirable materials degradation and the equipment is costly [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . In recent years, atomic force microscope (AFM) and scanning tunnelling microscope (STM) have been utilized for nanofabrication [CITATION_8] . The AFM tips are used as sharp tools to cut and remove materials, thus forming nano-grooves on the target surface [CITATION_9] . However, it is difficult, if not impossible, to fabricate protrusive nanostructures using AFM. Combining anodic oxidation with STM can be used to process protuberant structures on the surfaces of conductors and semiconductors under a given voltage [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] . Nevertheless, the anodic oxidation process is invalid for nonconductive STM tips or for insulator surfaces. Therefore, by virtue of the high precision and multifunction of AFM, it is of great importance to develop an accurate and straightforward method for fabricating protuberant nanostructures on insulator surfaces based on the proximal probe method.",
